               <p>PRISONER RILEY'S DEFENCE.</p>
               <p>I had been at work at the Hemp-wharf; at six I took my money, and went to see some ship-mates, and staid with them some considerable time; we went down the stairs, and called for a sculler several times; no boat could be found; this boat was laying on the stairs, that the scullers were laying at; going down, there were three men coming up the stairs, but whether they belonged to the boat I cannot say; I am satisfied that I am an honest man; I never was before any gentleman before.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17861025-118-person1426">
                  THOMAS
                   BUTLER
               <interp inst="t17861025-118-person1426" type="surname" value="BUTLER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17861025-118-person1426" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17861025-118-person1426" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            'S DEFENCE.</p>
               <p>I belong to a ship in the river, the New Hope; she lay down at Deptford; I was taking leave of my friends late on Saturday night, my clothes and things were on board; I got in liquor; we called sculler ten minutes; this boat was loose, and we intended to make her fast over the water.</p>
               <p>Were was that ship bound to? - To the South-seas; we all three belong to the same ship.</p>
               <p>Did you tell the watchman when you was taken, that you belonged to that ship? - I did not.</p>
               <p>Court to the watchman. Did you take these men into custody? - Yes, they gave no account of themselves, only they said, they cried scullers; I never heard any thing of it.</p>
               <p>Did any of the watermen hear them cry scullers? - No, and we lay close too.</p>
               <p>ALL FOUR <rs id="t17861025-118-verdict649" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t17861025-118-verdict649" type="verdictCategory" value="notGuilty"></interp>
               NOT GUILTY
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>Court. I hope these men will be more cautious in their conduct: and as to the watermen, I desire they will not understand, that we do not mean to protect their property; if ever they catch people that mean to take away their boats, we shall punish them here; but if they catch people in this mischievous way, taking their boats to carry them over the water, let them take them before a Magistrate, and he will put them into a way to make them pay for it, and that will stop them effectually.</p>
               <p>Tried by the first Middlesex Jury before Mr. 
               <persName id="t17861025-118-person1427">
                  Baron
                   EYRE
               <interp inst="t17861025-118-person1427" type="surname" value="EYRE"></interp>
